subsection.p:
From the electric potential for a point charge in front of a plane conductor found above we can determine the electric field by  \vec E = \vec{\nabla}\phi.  The components of the electric field are

	 E_x \amp = - \frac{\partial \phi_P}{\partial x} 
	 E_y \amp = - \frac{\partial \phi_P}{\partial y} 
	 E_z \amp = - \frac{\partial \phi_P}{\partial z}

Near the plate, electric field is equal constant with magnitude equal to \sigma/\epsilon_0 and perpendicular to the plates. 
Therefore, the distribution of negative charges on the plate can be determined from the difference of the normal component of the electric field across the surface.

	 \amp E_{z}|_{z>0} - E_z|_{z \lt 0} = \frac{\sigma_\text{ind}(x,y,0)}{\epsilon_0} 

where \sigma_\text{ind}(x,y,0) is the induced charge density distribution on the plate.  Using the z component of the electric field, we find the following for the surface charge density on the plate.

	\sigma_\text{ind}(x,y,z) = \frac{-qh/2\pi}{\left(x^2+y^2+h^2 \right)^{3/2}}

The total induced negative charge can be obtained by integrating  ind over the plate, which goes to infinity.  It is best to do this in the polar coordinates, (s,\phi,z).  The induced charge on the plate is function of only the radial coordinate s, which is integrated of the surface area of xy plane to yield that the induced charge is equal to the negative of the point charge of the point charge in front of the grounded plane.

	\sigma_\text{ind}(s) = \frac{-qh/2\pi}{\left(s^2+h^2 \right)^{3/2}}

We can integrate the surface charge density over the plane and obtain the net charge induced in the plane.

	q_\text{ind} = \int\sigma_\text{ind} 2\pi sds = -q
